**Abstract:**
Essay titled "Desirous knowledge" opening with Polanyi quotations on bodily knowledge and maps. Extensive analysis of Aristotle's distinction between speculative and practical knowledge. Argues the primacy of practical over speculative: knowledge is fundamentally practical/applicative, connected with desire and action. Shows how notions of truth-correspondence arise from linguistic objectification. Includes detailed appendix analyzing Devereux's article on Aristotelian practical wisdom.

**AI Recommendation:** Major theoretical essay on epistemology; continues 98-nov themes.

